        // ... etc ...
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList&lt;Person&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    	list.add(new Person(&quot;Jim&quot;,       &quot;Hawkins&quot;));
    	list.add(new Person(&quot;Alexander&quot;, &quot;Smollet&quot;));
    	list.add(new Person(&quot;David&quot;,     &quot;Livesy&quot;));
    
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; list.size(); i++) {
            if (list.get(i).getLastName().equals(&quot;Livesy&quot;)) { // &lt;-----
                System.out.println(&quot;Found matching name at index &quot; + i);
            }
        }
    }

If you have implemented the `.equals` method in `Employee` class you may just pass it to `.indexOf()`


    List&lt;Employee&gt; l = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    Employee e = new Employee(&quot;ID123&quot;);
    int idx = l.indexOf(e);

As the `ID` is unique, you don&#39;t need to check all the fields in the `.equals()` method, just check the `ID` : 


    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (o == null || getClass() != o.getClass()) return false;
        Employee employee = (Employee) o;
        return id == employee.id;
    }


------------

Or implement it yourself, using the same logic of `indexOf`

    int idx = -1;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; l.size(); i++) {
        if (e.getId() == l.get(i).getId()) {
            idx = i;
            break;
        }
    }

You can write it like this:

```java
public Employee getEmployee(String id) {
    for (Employee employee : employees) {
        if (employee.getId().equals(id)) {
            return employee;
        }
    }
    return null;
}
```

But it will be slow if there are a lot of employees in the list because it iterates over the list. If you want to look up employees quickly by ID, I would recommend you use a Map (e.g. `HashMap`) keyed on the id with Employee as the value.

Another alternative would be to ensure that the `Employee` objects in the list are kept in order of id. Then you could do a binary search of the list to find an Employee with a specific id.

A modern way is using the streams API:

```
public Optional&lt;Employee&gt; getEmployee(String id) {
    Optional&lt;Employee&gt; employee = employeesAL.stream()
          .filter(employee -&gt; id.equals(employee.getId()))
          .findAny();

    return employee;
}
```

This method returns `Optional&lt;Employee&gt;` because you can&#39;t guarantee that an employee can be found for every ID you pass in. [This page][1] has a good guide for working with Optionals.


  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/java-optional

The answers of users @azro and @elevate is correct. But if you&#39;re using Java 8 and up you can use the following to find an element:

    List&lt;Employee&gt; employeesAL = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    ....
    public Employee findEmployee(long id) {
        Optional&lt;Employee&gt; optionalEmployee = employeesAl.stream()
                                             .filter(e -&gt; e.getId() == id)
                                             .findFirst().orElse(null);
    }
**Note:** Note that returning null from a method is bad old habit. If you know how to use the Optional class, it is the better way of returning a value from a method which can be null; so you can inform the client the value can be null and it should handle this case.

